---> What is a Queue?
A **Queue** is a **linear data structure** that follows the rule:
### ðŸ‘‰ **FIFO â€“ First In, First Out**
âž¡ï¸ The element that enters **first** will leave **first**.

---> Real-Life Examples
* ðŸŽ¬ Movie theater line
* ðŸ–¨ï¸ Printer jobs
* ðŸŒ Web server requests
* ðŸš¦ Traffic signal waiting line
* ðŸ“ž Call center waiting calls

---> Basic Queue Terminology
| Term          | Meaning                          |
| ------------- | -------------------------------- |
| **Enqueue**   | Insert an element into the queue |
| **Dequeue**   | Remove an element from the queue |
| **Front**     | Position where deletion happens  |
| **Rear**      | Position where insertion happens |
| **Overflow**  | Queue is full                    |
| **Underflow** | Queue is empty                   |

---> How Queue Works (Concept)

FRONT â†’ [ A ][ B ][ C ] â† REAR

* **Enqueue** â†’ Insert at **REAR**
* **Dequeue** â†’ Remove from **FRONT**

---> FIFO Explained (Very Important for Interviews)
If elements are added in this order:

Enqueue: 10 â†’ 20 â†’ 30

They will be removed like:

Dequeue: 10 â†’ 20 â†’ 30

âž¡ï¸ **Same order in, same order out**

---> Queue Operations (With Examples)
### 1ï¸âƒ£ Enqueue (Insertion)
**Definition:**
Adding a new element at the **rear end** of the queue.
**Example:**

Queue: [10, 20]
Enqueue(30)
Queue becomes: [10, 20, 30]


### 2ï¸âƒ£ Dequeue (Deletion)
**Definition:**
Removing an element from the **front end** of the queue.
**Example:**

Queue: [10, 20, 30]
Dequeue()
Removed element: 10
Queue becomes: [20, 30]


### 3ï¸âƒ£ Peek / Front
**Definition:**
Returns the element at the **front** without removing it.
**Example:**

Queue: [20, 30]
Peek â†’ 20


### 4ï¸âƒ£ isEmpty()
Checks if the queue is empty.

Queue: [ ]
Result â†’ TRUE


### 5ï¸âƒ£ isFull()
Checks if the queue is full (mainly in array implementation).

---> Types of Queues
### 1ï¸âƒ£ Simple Queue (Linear Queue)
* Insertion at rear
* Deletion at front
* Problem: **wasted space** after deletions

### 2ï¸âƒ£ Circular Queue â­ (Very Important)
* Last position connects back to first
* Solves space wastage problem

[ ][ ][ ][ ]
 â†‘        â†“
 â””â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”˜


### 3ï¸âƒ£ Priority Queue
* Each element has a **priority**
* Higher priority element is served first
**Example:**
* Hospital emergency patients
* CPU task scheduling

### 4ï¸âƒ£ Deque (Double Ended Queue)
* Insertion & deletion allowed at **both ends**
Types:
* Input Restricted Deque
* Output Restricted Deque

---> Queue Implementation Methods
### 1ï¸âƒ£ Array Implementation
* Uses fixed size array
* Faster access
* Can cause overflow

### 2ï¸âƒ£ Linked List Implementation â­
* Dynamic size
* No overflow until memory full
* Extra memory for pointers

---> Time Complexity of Queue Operations
| Operation | Time |
|  | - |
| Enqueue   | O(1) |
| Dequeue   | O(1) |
| Peek      | O(1) |
| Search    | O(n) |

